Let's use the plot GUI to make a plot of this. Because the cell used to create the GUI is deleted when it is done being used for those testing it out the command sequence is:

from pandas_GUI import *
plot_pandas_GUI()

In [9]:
from plotly import graph_objects as go
Figure_1 = go.FigureWidget(layout_template="simple_white")
scat = go.Scatter(x = ethaneIR['1/CM'], y = ethaneIR['TRANSMITTANCE'],
        mode = 'lines', name = 'TRANSMITTANCE',)
Figure_1.add_trace(scat)
Figure_1.update_xaxes(title= '1/cm')
Figure_1.update_yaxes(title= 'transmittance')
Figure_1.update_layout(title = 'Figure_1', template = 'simple_white')

Many spectra are displayed as absorbance for the y-axis rather than transmittance, because absorbance is linearly proportional to the concentration of the absorbing species. The relation between absorbance and transmittance is: A=−log10(T),A=−log10(T), where A = the absorbance and T = the transmittance. Putting the command new_pandas_column_GUI() in the cell below and running the cell will provide the GUI that can be used to add an absorbance colume to the dataframe.

In [11]:
import numpy as np # Necessary for function calls
ethaneIR['absorbance'] = -np.log(ethaneIR['TRANSMITTANCE'])
ethaneIR # DataFrame name on last line of cell displays summary.

The plot_pandas_GUI() can be run in the next cell to plot the new column versus the '1/cm' or both for comparison.

In [13]:
from plotly import graph_objects as go
Figure_2 = go.FigureWidget(layout_template="simple_white")
scat = go.Scatter(x = ethaneIR['1/CM'], y = ethaneIR['TRANSMITTANCE'],
        mode = 'lines', name = 'TRANSMITTANCE',)
Figure_2.add_trace(scat)
scat = go.Scatter(x = ethaneIR['1/CM'], y = ethaneIR['absorbance'],
        mode = 'lines', name = 'absorbance',)
Figure_2.add_trace(scat)
Figure_2.update_xaxes(title= '1/cm', mirror = True)
Figure_2.update_yaxes(title= 'Signal', mirror = True)
Figure_2.update_layout(title = 'Comparison of Absorbance and Transmittance', template = 'simple_white')
